Week 14 IP - Dimensionality Reduction Techniques

1. Defining the Question

Specifying the data analytic question

Perform Dimensionality reduction on the sales dataset provided

Defining the metrics for success

This study will be considered succesful if:

  • Both PCA and TSNE are performed with clear visualizations made and explained

Understanding the Context

Dimensionality Reduction is reducing the number of variables in a dataset. Advantages of Dimensionality Reduction include:

  • A reduction in storage space
  • Fastens time required for computations
  • Takes care of multi-collinearity
  • Better visualization of data

This study is therefore important so as to avoid probelms such as overlapping, duplication in features or high features correlation that could arise from working with very large datasets.

7.Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

Principal components analysis (PCA) is a method for finding low-dimensional representations of a data set that retain as much of the original variation as possible. The idea is that each of the n observations lives in p-dimensional space, but not all of these dimensions are equally interesting. In PCA we look for a smaller number of dimensions that are as interesting as possible, where the concept of interesting is measured by the amount that the observations vary along each dimension. Each of the new dimensions found in PCA is a linear combination of the original p features

Data Pre-processing

  • PCA is sensitive to scale of measurement thus we should always standardize variables before applying PCA
  • PCA can only be applied to numerical data hence categorical variables need to be convereted to numerical data
#str(sales)
#selecting only numeric variables and omiting categorical variables (Invoice ID, branch, customer type, gender, product line, year, month, day, Time and payment)

## Proportion of Variance 0.000e+00
## Cumulative Proportion  1.000e+00

From the above, we have a total of 7 PCA components, out of which 4 will give us 100% of the information hence the other three components have very negligible contribution.

8.T Distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding - TSNE

T-SNE is a dimensionality reduction technique that is used for visualization of high dimensionality dataset. It makes it easy to understand and to explore relations between features in a dataset.

# Curating the sales data for analysis 
#

sales$Total = factor(sales$Total)

# For plotting

colors = rainbow(length(unique(sales$Total)))
names(colors) = unique(sales$Total)

** Conclusions**

From the above study, we have managed to perform dimensionality reduction using both PCA and TSNE techniques. From the PCA, 100% of the variance was obtained from 4 components hence we can work with these 4 components. From TSNE, we have observed clusters of the total variable
